font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">Bien que la plupart des cancers et des tumeurs ne soient pas héréditaires, chez certaines personnes, le risque de développer des tumeurs et/ou des tumeurs cancéreuses et/ou non-cancéreuses peut être dû à un gène transmis de génération en génération dans une famille. Si vous êtes la première personne de votre famille à avoir reçu un diagnostic de cancer ou de tumeur, cela n\'exclut pas une cause génétique en vous.</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">Après avoir recueilli vos antécédents médicaux et familiaux, la spécialiste en génétique discutera avec vous de la pertinence d\'un examen génétique (examen sanguin d\'ADN) dans votre situation. Si vous êtes candidat(e) aux examens génétiques, les avantages et les limites de ces examens ainsi que les résultats possibles de ces examens, seront discutés avec vous. </span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">À la fin de ce rendez-vous, vous serez en mesure de prendre une décision éclairée quant à savoir si les tests génétiques pourraient être utiles, soit à vous, à vos médecins et ou bien à d\'autres membres de votre famille.</span><!--EndFragment--><br/><br/></p>', '<p><b>What is the purpose of this appointment?</b></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">Your doctor has referred you to the Medical Genetics service. During your first appointment, you will meet with Mr. Evan Weber, a Genetic Counsellor, to discuss your personal medical and family history. This will involve drawing out your family tree in detail. The genetics specialist will then assess whether the history of cancer or tumours in yourself and/or other family members may have a genetic cause. If appropriate, you will be offered genetic testing (usually a blood test). This testing could help you and your family to better understand whether your cancer or tumour (or the cancers in your family) could be hereditary.</span></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">If a hereditary cause (i.e. a gene) for cancer or tumours has already been identified in your family, we will assess your personal risk to have inherited this gene and will review in detail the potential benefits/limitations of genetic testing for you.</span></p><p><b style="font-size: 14px;">Who will I meet at this appointment?</b></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">You will meet with Mr. Evan Weber, Genetic Counsellor at the McGill University Health Centre, and possibly a trainee in Medical Genetics.</span></p><p><b style="font-size: 14px;">Where will this appointment take place?</b></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">This appointment in Medical Genetics will take place at the Opal Medical Institution - Cancer Centre, Block D, Level S1, Room 1620 (D S1.1620). You need to check-in at the D S1.1620 reception. You can then have a seat in the waiting room. You will be notified on your phone and on the waiting room screens (Your first name and first three letters of your last name) when it\'s time to see Mr. Evan Weber.</span></p><p><b style="font-size: 14px;">How should I prepare for this appointment?</b></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">If you have been sent a family history questionnaire, please complete the information requested to the best of your ability and return the questionnaire to the Medical Genetics team or bring it with you to your first appointment. If you cannot provide precise details about your family history, please provide whatever information you do know.</span></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">If you have not been sent a questionnaire, then there is no specific preparation required for this appointment.</span></p><p><b style="font-size: 14px;">What should I bring to this appointment?</b></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">If you are being treated for a cancer or tumour outside of the MUHC, then please bring any information regarding your diagnosis with you to the appointment. This could be any pathology reports, doctor consultation notes, and/or your list of current medications/treatment(s). Please bring your valid Quebec Medicare Card (RAMQ) as well as your MUHC blue hospital card.</span></p><p><b style="font-size: 14px;">What should I expect during this appointment? </b></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">While most cancers or tumours are not hereditary, in some individuals, an increased risk to develop cancerous and/or non-cancerous growths/tumours may be due to a gene that is being passed on in a family from one generation to the next. If you are the first person in your family to be diagnosed with a cancer or tumour, this does not rule-out a genetic cause in you. </span></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">After collecting your personal medical and family history, the genetics specialist will discuss with you whether genetic testing (a DNA blood test) is appropriate in your case. If you are a candidate for genetic testing, the advantages and limitations of testing will be reviewed with you as well as what types of test results you might expect.</span></p><p><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">By the end of this visit, you will hopefully be able to make an informed decision about whether genetic testing could be helpful to you, your doctors, and potentially other family members.</span></p>', NULL, 26, 2, '#FFAB00', 1, '2000-01-01 00:00:00', 15, '2019-03-12 11:58:06', 'qI3ZufU3mc'),
(255, 'Appointment', 0, 'Rendez-vous de suivi avec M. Evan Weber, conseiller en génétique', 'Follow-Up Appointment with Mr. Evan Weber, Genetic Counsellor', '<p>..</p>', '<p><b style="font-size: 14px;">What is the purpose of this appointment?</b><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;"> </span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">In most cases, the purpose of the follow-up appointment is to discuss the results of any genetic testing that was offered to you at your previous visit in Medical Genetics.</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">In some cases, a follow-up appointment may be requested by yourself or your genetics specialist as a routine “check-in” to discuss:</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">- Your current health concerns or any changes in your health</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">- Results of your cancer screening tests</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">- Symptoms you may be experiencing</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">- Genetic risk for other family members</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><b style="font-size: 14px;"><br/>Who will I meet at this appointment?</b><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">You will meet with Mr. Evan Weber, Genetic Counsellor at the McGill University Health Centre, and possibly a trainee in Medical Genetics.</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><b style="font-size: 14px;"><br/>Where will this appointment take place?</b><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">Your follow-up appointment in Medical Genetics will take place at the Opal Medical Institution - Cancer Centre, Block D, Level S1, Room 1620 (D S1.1620). You need to check-in at the D S1.1620 reception. You can then have a seat in the waiting room. You will be notified on your phone and on the waiting room screens (Your first name and first three letters of your last name) when it\'s time to see Mr. Evan Weber.</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><b style="font-size: 14px;"><br/>How should I prepare for this appointment?</b><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">There is no specific preparation required for this appointment. If you are expecting to receive test results at this appointment, you are welcome to have a support person such as a family member or friend accompany you to your appointment.</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><b style="font-size: 14px;">What should I bring to this appointment?</b><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;"> Please bring your RAMQ card as well as your blue Opal General Hospital card.</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><b style="font-size: 14px;">What should I expect during this appointment?</b><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">You should expect to meet with Mr. Evan Weber, Genetic Counsellor, to discuss the results of any testing that was offered to you at your first visit. If you are found to test positive for a specific genetic change (“mutation”), the meaning of this result for you and other family members will be explained in detail. Based on your test results (positive, negative, or uncertain), the genetics specialist will discuss with you the most appropriate cancer screening and/or treatment based on your level of genetic risk. This information will then be communicated to your doctor(s) so that he/she can better care for you and your specific health needs. Genetic counselling services may also be offered to your family members, if appropriate. Please feel free to write down any questions you may have and bring them with you to the</span><br style="font-size: 14px;"/><span style="font-size: 14px;float: none;">follow-up appointment.</span><br/></p>', NULL, 22, 2, '#D50000', 1, '2000-01-01 00:00:00', 15, '2024-05-16 10:36:09', 'TdE8shwhm0'),
(256, 'Appointment', 0, 'Rendez-vous de consultation avec Mme Laura Palma, conseillère en génétique', 'Consultation Appointment with Ms. Laura Palma, Genetic Counsellor', '<p><b>Quel est le but de ce rendez-vous?</b><br/>Votre médecin vous a référé au service de génétique médicale. Lors de votre premier rendez-vous, vous rencontrerez Mme Laura Palma, conseillère en génétique, pour discuter de vos antécédents médicaux et familiaux. Votre arbre généalogique détaillé sera créé lors du rendez-vous. La spécialiste en génétique déterminera ensuite si vos antécédents de cancer ou de tumeurs et/ou ceux des autres membre de votre famille peuvent avoir une cause génétique. Si nécessaire, des examens génétiques vous seront proposés (généralement une prise de sang). Ces examens pourraient vous aider, ainsi que votre famille, à mieux comprendre si votre cancer ou votre tumeur (ou les cancers des membres de votre famille) peuvent être héréditaires.<br/><br/>Si une cause héréditaire (un gène, par exemple) du cancer ou des tumeurs a déjà été identifiée dans votre famille, nous évaluerons votre risque personnel d\'avoir hérité de ce gène et examinerons en détail les avantages/limites potentiels de vous faire subir des examens génétiques.<br/><br/><b>Qui vais-je rencontrer lors de ce rendez-vous? </b><br/>Vous rencontrerez Mme Laura Palma, conseillère en génétique à l\'Établissement Médical Opal et possiblement un(e) stagiaire en génétique médicale.<br/><br/><b>Où aura lieu ce rendez-vous?</b><br/>Votre rendez-vous aura lieu à l\'Établissement Médical Opal, Centre du cancer, bloc D, niveau S1, salle 1620 (D S1.1620). Vous devrez vous enregistrer à la réception au D S1.1620. Vous pouvez ensuite prendre place dans la salle d’attente. Vous serez averti(e) sur votre téléphone et sur les écrans de la salle d’attente (votre prénom suivi des trois premières lettres de votre nom de famille) quand Mme Palma est prête à vous voir. <br/><br/><b>Comment dois-je me préparer pour ce rendez-vous?</b><br/>Si un questionnaire sur vos antécédents familiaux vous a préalablement été envoyé, veuillez le compléter de votre mieux et le renvoyer à l\'équipe de génétique médicale ou l\'apporter à votre premier rendez-vous. Si vous ne pouvez pas fournir des détails précis sur vos antécédents familiaux, veuillez fournir les informations que vous connaissez.<br/>Si vous n\'avez pas reçu de questionnaire, aucune préparation spécifique n\'est requise pour ce rendez-vous.<br/><br/><b>Que dois-je apporter à ce rendez-vous? </b><br/><br/>Si vous êtes traité(e) pour un cancer ou une tumeur à l\'extérieur du CUSM, veuillez rapporter toute information concernant votre diagnostic. Il peut s\'agir de rapports de pathologie, de notes de consultation médicale et/ou votre liste de médicaments/traitements actuels. Veuillez apporter votre carte d\'assurance maladie (RAMQ) et votre carte d\'hôpital bleue du Établissement Médical Opal.<br/><br/><b>À quoi devrais-je m\'attendre lors de ce rendez-vous?</b><br/><br/>Bien que la plupart des cancers et des tumeurs ne soient pas héréditaires, chez certaines personnes, le risque de développer des tumeurs et/ou des tumeurs cancéreuses et/ou non-cancéreuses peut être dû à un gène transmis de génération en génération dans une famille. Si vous êtes la première personne de votre famille à avoir reçu un diagnostic de cancer ou de tumeur, cela n\'exclut pas une cause génétique en vous.<br/>Après avoir recueilli vos antécédents médicaux et familiaux, la spécialiste en génétique discutera avec vous de la pertinence d\'un examen génétique (examen sanguin d\'ADN) dans votre situation. Si vous êtes candidat(e) aux examens génétiques, les avantages et les limites de ces examens ainsi que les résultats possibles de ces examens, seront discutés avec vous. <br/>À la fin de ce rendez-vous, vous serez en mesure de prendre une décision éclairée quant à savoir si les tests génétiques pourraient être utiles, soit à vous, à vos médecins et ou bien à d\'autres membres de votre famille.</p>', '<p><b>What is the purpose of this appointment?</b><br/><br/>Your doctor has referred you to the Medical Genetics service. During your first appointment, you will meet with Ms. Laura Palma, a Genetic Counsellor, to discuss your personal medical and family history. This will involve drawing out your family tree in detail. The genetics specialist will then assess whether the history of cancer or tumours in yourself and/or other family members may have a genetic cause. If appropriate, you will be offered genetic testing (usually a blood test). This testing could help you and your family to better understand whether your cancer or tumour (or the cancers in your family) could be hereditary.<br/><br/>If a hereditary cause (i.e. a gene) for cancer or tumours has already been identified in your family, we will assess your personal risk to have inherited this gene and will review in detail the potential benefits/limitations of genetic testing for you.<br/><br/><b>Who will I meet at this appointment?</b><br/><br/>You will meet with Ms. Laura Palma, Genetic Counsellor at the McGill University Health Centre, and possibly a trainee in Medical Genetics.<br/><br/><b>Where will this appointment take place?</b><br/><br/>This appointment in Medical Genetics will take place at the Opal Medical Institution - Cancer Centre, Block D, Level S1, Room 1620 (D S1.1620). You need to check-in at the D S1.1620 reception. You can then have a seat in the waiting room. You will be notified on your phone and on the waiting room screens (Your first name and first three letters of your last name) when it\'s time to see Ms. Laura Palma.<br/><b><br/>How should I prepare for this appointment?</b><br/><br/>If you have been sent a family history questionnaire, please complete the information requested to the best of your ability and return the questionnaire to the Medical Genetics team or bring it with you to your first appointment. If you cannot provide precise details about your family history, please provide whatever information you do know.<br/><br/>If you have not been sent a questionnaire, then there is no specific preparation required for this appointment.<br/><br/><b>What should I bring to this appointment?</b><br/><br/>If you are being treated for a cancer or tumour outside of the MUHC, then please bring any information regarding your diagnosis with you to the appointment. This could be any pathology reports, doctor consultation notes, and/or your list of current medications/treatment(s). Please bring your valid Quebec Medicare Card (RAMQ) as well as your MUHC blue hospital card.<b><br/><br/>What should I expect during this appointment? </b><br/><br/>While most cancers or tumours are not hereditary, in some individuals, an increased risk to develop cancerous and/or non-cancerous growths/tumours may be due to a gene that is being passed on in a family from one generation to the next.  If you are the first person in your family to be diagnosed with a cancer or tumour, this does not rule-out a genetic cause in you.  <br/><br/>After collecting your personal medical and family history, the genetics specialist will discuss with you whether genetic testing (a DNA blood test) is appropriate in your case.  If you are a candidate for genetic testing, the advantages and limitations of testing will be reviewed with you as well as what types of test results you might expect.<br/><br/>By the end of this visit, you will hopefully be able to make an informed decision about whether genetic testing could be helpful to you, your doctors, and potentially other family members.<br/></p>', NULL, 26, 2, '#FFAB00', 1, '2000-01-01 00:00:00', 15, '2019-03-12 11:53:58', 'qI3ZufU3mc'),
